# Defining the function to get image as a list
def get_image_list(image_path):
  train_image_dir = os.listdir(image_path)
  trainImageList=[]
  for i in train_image_dir:
    for f in os.listdir(os.path.join(image_path, i)):
        ext = os.path.splitext(f)[1]
        if ext == '.jpg' or ext == '.jpeg':
          trainImageList.append("{}/{}".format(i,f))
  return trainImageList
In [11]:
# Defining the function to map images with classes
def map_image_metadata(image_base_path, annotate_metadata, image_path_list):
  image_path_lst_split = [i.split('/')[1] for i in image_path_list]
  annotate_metadata["car_image_path"] = annotate_metadata.apply(lambda row: image_base_path+'/'+ image_path_list[image_path_lst_split.index(row['image_file'])], axis=1)
  return annotate_metadata

# Creating a function to display the boundingbox
def boundingbox_image(df):
  img = cv2.imread(df.car_image_path,1)
  x0=df.x0
  x1=df.x1
  y0=df.y0
  y1=df.y1

  fig, ax = plt.subplots(1)
  ax.imshow(img)
  rect = patches.Rectangle((x0,y0), (x1-x0),(y1-y0),linewidth=2.5, edgecolor='g', facecolor='none')
  ax.add_patch(rect)
  plt.title(df.class_name)
  plt.show()

EDA of Car Dataset (We received the comment from milestone 1 evaluator)¶

  • The code performs an exploratory data analysis (EDA) of a car dataset using box plots.
  • The box plots show the distribution of the a0 and b0 columns (coordinates of the top-left corner of the bounding boxes) for each car class.
  • The code also prints some insights from the EDA, such as the most common car class and the average values of the a0 and b0 columns.

    • In [26]:
    import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def eda(df):

  ### Univariate analysis ###

  # Histogram of the class column
  plt.hist(df['class'])
  plt.xlabel('Car class')
  plt.ylabel('Number of cars')
  plt.title('Distribution of car classes')
  plt.show()

  # Box plot of the a0, b0, a1, and b1 columns
  plt.boxplot([df['x0'], df['y0'], df['x1'], df['y1']])
  plt.xlabel('Coordinate')
  plt.ylabel('Value')
  plt.title('Distribution of bounding box coordinates')
  plt.show()

  # Bar chart of the number of cars of each class
  plt.bar(df['class'].unique(), df['class'].value_counts())
  plt.xlabel('Car class')
  plt.ylabel('Number of cars')
  plt.title('Number of cars of each class')
  plt.show()

  ### Bivariate analysis ###

  # Scatter plot of the a0 and b0 columns
  plt.scatter(df['x0'], df['y0'])
  plt.xlabel('x0')
  plt.ylabel('y0')
  plt.title('Relationship between a0 and b0')
  plt.show()

  # Scatter plot of the a1 and b1 columns
  plt.scatter(df['x1'], df['y1'])
  plt.xlabel('x1')
  plt.ylabel('y1')
  plt.title('Relationship between a1 and b1')
  plt.show()

  # Insights
  print('The most common car class is:', df['class'].value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).index[0])
print("EDA Visualizations for Train Image")
eda(train_Annotate)
print("EDA Visualizations for Test Image")
eda(test_Annotate)

    # Defining the function to resize all the images
def resize_image_data(annotate):
    resized_images = []
    images_boundingbox = []
    images_class = []

    for index, rows in annotate.iterrows():
        img = cv2.UMat(cv2.imread(rows['car_image_path'],1)).get()
        try:
          img_resized = cv2.resize(img,(Image_Width,Image_Height), interpolation = cv2.INTER_AREA)
          img_hw = np.zeros((4,1), dtype=np.float32)
          img_hw[0] = rows['x0']*Image_Width/img.shape[1]
          img_hw[1] = rows['y0']*Image_Height/img.shape[0]
          img_hw[2] = (rows['x1']-rows['x0'])*Image_Width/img.shape[1]
          img_hw[3] = (rows['y1']-rows['y0'])*Image_Height/img.shape[0]

          images_boundingbox.append(img_hw)
          resized_images.append(preprocess_input(np.array(img_resized, dtype=np.float32)))
          images_class.append(rows['class'])

          del img, img_resized, img_hw
        except:
          break

    return resized_images, images_boundingbox, images_class

    return (x*sigmoid(beta*x))

    # Define the function for classification model
def create_classification_model(trainable=True):
    model = MobileNetV2(input_shape=(224,224,3), alpha=1.0, include_top=False, weights='imagenet',
            classifier_activation='softmax')

    for layer in model.layers:
        layer.trainable = trainable

    x=model.output
    x=Dropout(0.2)(x)
    x=BatchNormalization(epsilon=0.0001)(x)
    x=Flatten()(x)
    x=Dense(1024,activation='relu')(x)      # add dense layers - the model can learn more complex functions and classify for better results.
    x=Dropout(0.2)(x)
    x=BatchNormalization(epsilon=0.0001)(x)
    #x=Dense(1024,activation='swish')(x)    # dense layer 2
    x=Dense(512,activation='relu')(x)       # dense layer 3
    x=Dense(196,activation='softmax')(x)    # final layer with softmax activation

    return Model(inputs=model.input, outputs=x)
    In [38]:
    # Define the function for predicting the bounding box to the given image
def generate_boundingbox_model(trainable=True):
    model = MobileNetV2(input_shape=(224,224,3), alpha=1.0, include_top=False, weights='imagenet',
            classifier_activation='softmax')

    for layer in model.layers:
        layer.trainable = trainable

    x0 = model.layers[-1].output
    x1 = Conv2D(4, kernel_size=7, name="coords")(x0)
    x2 = Reshape((4,))(x1)

    return Model(inputs=model.input, outputs=x2)

    # Define the function: IOU for evaluation metrics of bounding box

def IOU(y_true, y_pred):
    intersections = 0
    unions = 0

    # set the types so we are sure what type we are using
    gt = y_true
    pred = y_pred

    # Compute interection of predicted (pred) and ground truth (gt) bounding boxes
    diff_width = np.minimum(gt[:,0] + gt[:,2], pred[:,0] + pred[:,2]) - np.maximum(gt[:,0], pred[:,0])
    diff_height = np.minimum(gt[:,1] + gt[:,3], pred[:,1] + pred[:,3]) - np.maximum(gt[:,1], pred[:,1])
    intersection = diff_width * diff_height

    # Compute union
    area_gt = gt[:,2] * gt[:,3]
    area_pred = pred[:,2] * pred[:,3]
    union = area_gt + area_pred - intersection

    # Compute intersection and union over multiple boxes
    for j, _ in enumerate(union):
      if union[j] > 0 and intersection[j] > 0 and union[j] >= intersection[j]:
        intersections += intersection[j]
        unions += union[j]

    # Compute IOU. Use epsilon to prevent division by zero
    iou = np.round(intersections / (unions + tensorflow.keras.backend.epsilon()), 4)

    # This must match the type used in py_function
    iou = iou.astype(np.float32)

    return iou
    In [40]:
    # Define the function to Get IoU value based on the provided and predicted bounding box
def IoU(y_true, y_pred):
    iou = tensorflow.py_function(IOU, [y_true, y_pred], Tout=tensorflow.float32)
    return iou

epochs = range(len(IoU_score))

# plotting score
plt.plot(epochs, IoU_score, label = 'training: IoU score' )
plt.plot(epochs, val_IoU_score, label = 'validation: IoU score' )
plt.title('Training and val accuracy(bounding box)')
plt.legend(loc = 'lower right')
plt.figure()

# plotting loss
plt.plot(epochs, loss, label = 'training loss' )
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, label = 'val loss' )
plt.legend(loc = 'upper right')
plt.title('Training and val loss(bounding box)')
plt.show()
